# Co-Producer Infrastructure Recovery Plan

## Decision

Do not keep iterating on the current architecture as the primary production path.

Keep Max for Live only where it is strong:
- in-set UI
- audio tapping / metering
- lightweight Live observation when needed

Move the authoritative write bridge out of Max for Live and into a dedicated Ableton control-surface / remote-script integration.

Reason:
- repeated failures are happening on the first write primitive: `create_midi_track`
- that means the current bridge is not failing at product logic, it is failing at the platform boundary
- if the first primitive is unreliable, every higher-level promise built on top of it is unreliable too

## Findings

### 1. The current write path is not trustworthy

Current production write flow:
- planner generates an `ActionPlan`
- desktop app sends it over localhost WebSocket
- `node.script` forwards into `js live-observer.js`
- `live-observer.js` mutates Live through the Live API

This is the wrong place to carry production reliability.

Observed evidence in this repo and current testing:
- the bridge can connect and exchange snapshots
- the self-test fails on `create_midi_track`
- repeated retries, deferred tasks, patch-level message scheduling, and post-step verification did not make the first write primitive reliable

Impact:
- every feature above this layer is blocked
- any “production-ready coproducer” claim is false until the write surface itself is proven

### 2. The system mixes a demo planner with a DAW automation claim

Current planner behavior in [planner.ts](/Users/aleksander/Documents/Development/co-producer/packages/core/src/planner.ts) is still a heuristic generator with a narrow command set.

It can:
- infer role
- pick a native instrument/effect chain
- generate MIDI notes heuristically

It cannot yet:
- reason over real audio from the Live set in a trustworthy way
- inspect plugin-specific state in a robust way
- adapt decisions from a verified mutation result
- operate as a closed-loop agent that listens, changes, re-measures, and improves

Impact:
- the current system is closer to a guided native-device macro planner than a true co-producer

### 3. The audio intelligence path is still placeholder-level

Current bridge-side analysis in [live-observer.js](/Users/aleksander/Documents/Development/co-producer/bridges/max-for-live/live-observer.js) is a density-derived placeholder, not actual signal analysis.

That means the app does not yet truly:
- listen to the track
- compare actual spectral/dynamic balance
- drive mixing/mastering decisions from the real signal path

Impact:
- “mixing”, “mastering”, and “listen and improve” are not credible product claims yet

### 4. The safety model depends on snapshot truth, but the current snapshot source is not authoritative enough

The architecture assumes:
- plan generated from snapshot revision
- write command applied to the live set
- fresh snapshot proves the mutation occurred

That only works if the write path and snapshot source are both authoritative.

Right now:
- mock mode and real mode share too much product surface
- snapshot truth depends on a Max bridge that is itself not yet a proven write authority

Impact:
- revision safety exists on paper, but not yet on a reliable control substrate

### 5. The product scope is wider than the actual platform support

Current user expectation:
- create tracks, clips, devices, notes
- mix
- master
- “perform any action on demand”
- eventually support arbitrary production tasks

Current platform support:
- Live Object Model / Max for Live can access a bounded set of Live objects
- native-device insertion and clip/track manipulation are feasible when the bridge is reliable
- arbitrary third-party plugin control, deep session introspection, and true audio-driven autonomous production are separate problems

Impact:
- the app needs an explicit capability matrix instead of a broad “can do anything in Ableton” promise

## Target Architecture

### A. Split read, write, and audio into separate runtime responsibilities

#### 1. Desktop orchestrator

Keep Electron as the control plane:
- chat UX
- orchestration
- plan generation
- policy / safety checks
- execution review
- trace logging
- durable session state

#### 2. Primary write bridge: custom Ableton control surface / remote script

Inference from official Ableton support surfaces:
- Ableton supports installed control-surface / remote-script integrations
- Live 11+ moved remote scripts to Python 3
- this is the correct place for authoritative session mutation, not a Max device pretending to be a transaction engine

Production role:
- create / rename / color / arm / delete tracks
- create / duplicate / delete clips
- write MIDI
- insert native devices
- set native parameters
- read selected track / selected clip / devices / session view state
- publish authoritative execution results back to the desktop app

Requirement:
- every supported command must be implemented in the remote script first
- no UI promise ships before the remote-script command passes manual QA on the supported Live versions

#### 3. Secondary Live companion: Max for Live

Use Max for Live only where it adds leverage:
- in-session UX
- audio observation
- metering taps
- transport-linked helpers
- optional visual / debugging device

Do not use it as the primary write authority.

#### 4. Dedicated audio analysis path

Add a real signal-analysis pipeline:
- selected track tap
- master tap
- exported reference ingestion
- loudness / crest / spectral balance / stereo width / transient / note-density analysis

Possible packaging options:
- Max for Live audio device for taps
- desktop-side analysis workers
- explicit buffer/render handoff instead of fake placeholder features

### B. Introduce a strict capability matrix

The app should explicitly support only these v1 write actions:
- create MIDI track
- create audio track
- create return track if the platform surface supports it reliably
- rename / color / arm tracks
- create MIDI clip
- replace MIDI notes
- insert supported native instruments
- insert supported native audio effects
- set supported native parameters

Not v1:
- arbitrary VST/plugin control
- arbitrary mix/master actions with no explicit command support
- destructive editing without confirmation
- “any action on demand”

### C. Make execution closed-loop

Every execution request should be:
1. planned
2. capability-checked
3. executed by the authoritative write bridge
4. re-read from Live
5. validated against expected mutation
6. surfaced with structured trace

If verification fails:
- mark the batch failed
- capture exact bridge logs
- suggest next diagnostic step

### D. Add a real production-state model

The state model should separately track:
- transport
- arrangement state
- selected track / clip / device
- device chains
- gain staging summary
- spectral / loudness summary
- reference-file comparisons
- execution traces
- last known verified command result

Mock mode should become a clearly separate sandbox, not a silent fallback with near-identical UX.

## Proposed Migration Plan

### Phase 0: Stop widening scope on the current Max-write architecture

Do not add more command types to the current Max write bridge.

Only keep enough code to:
- preserve current research
- keep the UI usable
- support a temporary snapshot / audio helper path

### Phase 1: Build the authoritative write bridge

Deliverables:
- custom control-surface / remote-script package
- local IPC channel between Live integration and desktop app
- supported command suite with deterministic IDs and structured results
- hardcoded self-test matrix

Acceptance:
- `create_midi_track`
- `create_audio_track`
- `create_midi_clip`
- `replace_clip_notes`
- `insert_native_device`
- `set_device_parameter`
- `name_track`
- `set_track_color`
- `arm_track`

All must pass manual QA on supported environments before expanding scope.

### Phase 2: Make context authoritative

Deliverables:
- selected track sync
- selected clip sync
- device-chain sync
- session snapshot from the authoritative bridge
- clear capability flags per command

Acceptance:
- selecting a track in Live updates the app within 1 second
- creating a track or clip is reflected back in the next verified snapshot

### Phase 3: Add real audio listening

Deliverables:
- selected-track audio tap
- master tap
- desktop-side signal analysis workers
- reference matching and delta suggestions

Acceptance:
- app can explain concrete mix imbalances from the actual signal
- app can compare current master against imported references with real feature deltas

### Phase 4: Upgrade planning into a proper coproducer loop

Deliverables:
- retrieval over project context
- structured planning modes
- self-critique / revise loop
- multi-turn task memory
- mix / arrangement / sound-design specialists

Acceptance:
- user can ask for track building, arranging, mix critique, and revision suggestions grounded in the current set

## Immediate Repo Changes Recommended

### 1. Reframe the product docs

Update public docs to say:
- current app is an experimental Ableton copilot
- authoritative Live write control is under rebuild
- Max for Live write execution is not production-ready

### 2. Add a new architecture document for the remote-script pivot

Create:
- `docs/control-surface-architecture.md`

Include:
- process model
- command transport
- verified capability matrix
- supported Live versions
- QA matrix

### 3. Freeze Max write-surface expansion

Do not add:
- more write commands
- more “AI autonomy” claims
- broader plugin promises

Until the authoritative bridge exists.

### 4. Build a hardware-in-the-loop QA workflow

Required:
- scripted desktop-side integration tests
- manual Live QA checklist
- versioned test matrix:
  - macOS version
  - Ableton Live version
  - Max version
  - device package version

## What “Production Ready” Actually Means Here

For this app, production ready should mean:
- deterministic bridge connection
- deterministic track/clip/device mutations
- authoritative state sync back from Live
- explicit unsupported actions
- real audio analysis instead of placeholders
- no false success states
- manual QA across supported environments

Until then, the app should not describe itself as able to “perform any action on demand”.

